# Array Sorting

| | |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Input** | Standard input |
| **Output** | Standard output |

### Problem Statement
Sort the given array in non-decreasing order.

### Input Format
- The first line contains a single natural number $n$ ($1 \le n \le 10^5$) — the number of elements in the array.
- The next line contains the elements of the array — $n$ integers, each not exceeding $10^9$ in absolute value.

### Output Format
Print the elements of the array in non-decreasing order.

### Notes
**Using built-in sorting functions is prohibited.** You must implement a sorting algorithm yourself.

### Examples
| Input | Output |
| :--- | :--- |
| `3` <br> `2 1 3` | `1 2 3` |

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

void qsort(int* A, int L, int R) {
    if (R - L <= 1) 
        return;
    int mid_index = L + (R - L) / 2;
    int mid = A[mid_index];
    
    int x = L, y = L;
    for (int i = L; i < R; ++i) {
        if (A[i] < mid) {
            swap(A[i], A[x]);
            if (x != y) {
                swap(A[i], A[y]);
            }
            ++x; 
            ++y;
        } 
        else if (A[i] == mid) {
            swap(A[i], A[y]);
            ++y;
        }
    }
    qsort(A, L, x);
    qsort(A, y, R);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    
    int* arr = new 
      int[n];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> arr[i];
    }
    
    if (n > 0) {
        qsort(arr, 0, n);
    }
    
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }
    
    return 0;
}


